{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_21","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' references_cache/PMID_12769863.md\"","aggregated_output":"---\nreference_id: PMID:12769863\ntitle: \"An NMD pathway in yeast involving accelerated deadenylation and exosome-mediated 3'-->5' degradation.\"\nauthors:\n- Mitchell P\n- Tollervey D\njournal: Mol Cell\nyear: '2003'\ndoi: 10.1016/s1097-2765(03)00190-4\nkeywords:\n- \"3' Untranslated Regions/genetics\"\n- \"5' Untranslated Regions/genetics\"\n- \"Adaptor Proteins, Signal Transducing\"\n- Adenine/metabolism\n- \"Cells, Cultured\"\n- \"Codon, Nonsense/genetics\"\n- Eukaryotic Cells/metabolism\n- \"Exoribonucleases/genetics, metabolism\"\n- \"GTP-Binding Proteins/genetics, metabolism\"\n- Protein Biosynthesis/genetics\n- \"RNA Helicases/genetics, metabolism\"\n- \"RNA, Messenger/genetics, metabolism\"\n- \"Saccharomyces cerevisiae/genetics, metabolism\"\n- \"Saccharomyces cerevisiae Proteins/genetics, metabolism\"\n- Signal Transduction/genetics\ncontent_type: abstract_only\n---\n\n# An NMD pathway in yeast involving accelerated deadenylation and exosome-mediated 3'-->5' degradation.\n**Authors:** Mitchell P, Tollervey D\n**Journal:** Mol Cell (2003)\n**DOI:** [10.1016/s1097-2765(03)00190-4](https://doi.org/10.1016/s1097-2765(03)00190-4)\n\n## Content\n\n1. Mol Cell. 2003 May;11(5):1405-13. doi: 10.1016/s1097-2765(03)00190-4.\n\nAn NMD pathway in yeast involving accelerated deadenylation and exosome-mediated \n3'-->5' degradation.\n\nMitchell P(1), Tollervey D.\n\nAuthor information:\n(1)Wellcome Trust Centre for Cell Biology, Institute for Cell and Molecular \nBiology, King's Buildings, University of Edinburgh, EH9 3JR, United Kingdom. \npmitch@holyrood.ed.ac.uk\n\nEukaryotic mRNAs containing premature termination codons are subjected to \naccelerated turnover, known as nonsense-mediated decay (NMD). Recognition of \ntranslation termination events as premature requires a surveillance complex, \nwhich includes the RNA helicase Upf1p. In Saccharomyces cerevisiae, NMD provokes \nrapid decapping followed by 5'-->3' exonucleolytic decay. Here we report an \nalternative, decapping-independent NMD pathway involving deadenylation and \nsubsequent 3'-->5' exonucleolytic decay. Accelerated turnover via this pathway \nrequired Upf1p and was blocked by the translation inhibitor cycloheximide. \nDegradation of the deadenylated mRNA required the Rrp4p and Ski7p components of \nthe cytoplasmic exosome complex, as well as the putative RNA helicase Ski2p. We \nconclude that recognition of NMD substrates by the Upf surveillance complex can \ntarget mRNAs to rapid deadenylation and exosome-mediated degradation.\n\nDOI: 10.1016/s1097-2765(03)00190-4\nPMID: 12769863 [Indexed for MEDLINE]","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
